	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		Anyone standing outside of the conference room door would have thought that Steve Balmer was inside throwing chairs around.  Certain members of Treesoft's management team were not happy with my briefing."Gentleman, if I may continue ..." I said with my hands raised in front of me.  "A number of your questions will be answered in this briefing." <br/><br/>The room settled down abruptly as I switched the slides of my Keynote presentation. <br/><br/>"When my associate noticed that P2P traffic was entering and leaving the Treesoft network, we investigated immediately.  The traffic was due to a P2P client installed on Sven's workstation.  There were no firewall safeguards in place to prevent this application from working as designed.   Through our investigation, we learned that while Sven claimed to have only kept the application running while searching for specific music and video files, we discovered that the application was, in fact, running 24/7.  The photographs on this slide are digital photographs of the limewire configuration, and of the documents being shared.  You'll notice that the six documents found on the internet are on this list." I explained.<br/><br/>Scrap stood up from his seat and continued the briefing.<br/><br/>"After we isolated the source of the traffic (Sven's workstation), we made a tactical decision to immediately close the point of the breach as quietly as possible.  I initiated a block of the P2P traffic by performing an "ARP spoof/poisoning" of Sven's workstation.  I directed all traffic to and from Sven's workstation to our monitoring machine.  At the monitoring machine, I dropped all P2P traffic in transit and let the rest of the traffic through.  This procedure made the P2P client think that it couldn't achieve a connection, which served the purpose of closing the breach.  We used this approach because we did not want to directly involve Treesoft networking staff in the technical portion of our investigation." <br/><br/>A quiet murmur began between a few members of the executive management team, their eyes fixated on our presentation.<br/><br/>I moved to the next slide.<br/><br/>"My associate was able to pinpoint which P2P clients on the internet had downloaded the confidential documents.  As you can see on this slide, all of the documents were downloaded by a single IP address that is owned by Gamersbeatches." I said with a wave of my paw.<br/><br/>John was holding his head in his hand, shaking it from side to side in disbelief.   Dave had started typing on his blackberry.  Ed, being the astute legal begal, was writing pages and pages of notes.<br/><br/>Peter appeared to be pretty annoyed and spoke up.<br/><br/>"Chief, let me make sure I have this straight.  You're telling us that an employee unintentionally shared confidential documents to the outside world through a P2P client, and a gaming web site just happened to find these documents?" <br/><br/>I flipped to the next slide and addressed Peter.<br/><br/>"Yes and no.  We suspected that the sharing properties of Sven's limewire application were being manipulated without his knowledge.  While Sven was in the office, his limewire application appeared to only share music and video files.  Somehow, these properties were being changed after hours.  Our next step was to set up surveillance on Sven's workstation to see if the changes were being made physically at the workstation, or possibly through some type of remote control software." <br/><br/>With a few clicks and several adjustments to the display projector, I queued up a video clip.<br/><br/>"This video was taken last night.  We have examined the video very thoroughly, and believe we now know who is making changes to Sven's application while he is gone." I said as I clicked the 'play' icon on the video clip.<br/><br/> The clip showed the inside of Sven's work area.  The camera inside the Scrapbag was positioned perfectly.  A few moments into the clip, a figure appeared.<br/><br/>Eric looked confused.<br/><br/>He was standing in front of Sven's workstation, manipulating the mouse and clicking through multiple windows on the screen.  First, he brought up Limewire from the minimized icon.  He then clicked through multiple levels of configuration screens, and added several key directories to the shared resources.  However, things weren't working the way he wanted.<br/><br/>The clock next to Sven's monitor read 08:02 PM.  After several minutes of attempted connection troubleshooting, Eric returned the desktop and windows to their normal configuration and left the office.<br/><br/>I stopped the video and turned my attention to the stunned members of Treesoft management seated at the conference room table.  Within seconds, everyone started talking at once in loud, passionate voices.<br/><br/>"Gentlemen, gentlemen ... PLEASE!"  I begged.  "Let me finish my presentation." <br/><br/>The room gradually quieted down.<br/><br/>"It is highly probable that Eric has been changing these application settings every night since a few days before the 'six documents' appeared on the internet.  According to the door reports, Eric and the cleaning crew are typically the only people here after 6PM.  In the video, Eric is confused because limewire is no longer able to connect out to the internet.  He gives up and leaves the area.  We were unable to find evidence of any other tampering of Sven's workstation." I said with another change of the slides.<br/><br/>John interrupted me with a loud grunting noise.  "Let's not gloss over this whole 'Gamersbeatches' thing.  If I'm hearing you correctly, you're saying that we have one employee trying to frame another employee, or just get that employee fired?"<br/><br/>I leaned over the conference room table and placed my paws on either side of my notebook.<br/><br/>"John, there are a lot more employees involved than Sven and Eric."<br/><br/>John appeared to have stopped breathing.<br/><br/><b>Coming Up Next: The Conclusion!!!  Who else was involved at Treesoft?  And why?</b><br/><br/>Chief<br/><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132408/http://www.esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=65096-060320-568092-35"><img alt="esbn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132408im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/esbnicon.asp?id=6509606032056809235" border="0"> 65096-060320-568092-35</a> Rate content: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132408/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=6509606032056809235&amp;rate=yes"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132408im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbup.gif" border="0"></a><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132408/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=6509606032056809235&amp;rate=no"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132408im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbdown.gif" border="0"></a><br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132408im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/barcode.asp?code=6509606032056809235&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"></p><p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
